        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 7-year-old girl in Czechia who is brought in by her parent for a sore throat consistent with acute pharyngitis [MEDDIALOG:J02.9:0, SNOMED:J02.9]. She looks tired and mildly uncomfortable, speaks less than usual because swallowing makes her throat hurt, and intermittently points to her throat when asked what is bothering her [SNOMED:J02.9]. Her parent also mentions some stomach ache since the illness began [SNOMED:J02.9].\n\nAt home, {patientName} is normally active and sociable, enjoying school, drawing, and playing with friends after class. Since becoming ill, she has preferred to stay on the couch, drink small sips, and avoid scratchy foods because of throat discomfort [SNOMED:J02.9]. There is no evidence provided of other unusual symptoms, so the presentation is kept focused on pharyngitis and stomach ache [SNOMED:J02.9].\n\nShe lives with her family and attends primary school, where exposure to common childhood infections is plausible. Her parent reports the symptoms started acutely and are concerning mainly because of the throat pain and reduced comfort with eating and drinking [SNOMED:J02.9]. The family is worried but attentive, and they have come for assessment to clarify whether this is a straightforward throat infection and how best to keep her comfortable [MEDDIALOG:J02.9:0]."
          }
        ]
      }
